\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring TransactionAutoConfiguration**\\n\\nI'm investigating how TransactionAutoConfiguration enables @Transactional and creates TransactionTemplate and TransactionalOperator. I believe I can test the creation of TransactionTemplate without extra dependencies since the platform manager is already there. It seems this feature isn't fully covered, as existing configurations don’t register it. I think I could add a test to verify it respects conditions for a single candidate. I'll also check if it backs off when user-defined TransactionOperations are present, ensuring there are no duplicates in my testing flow.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating TransactionAutoConfiguration issues**\\n\\nI’m looking into a potential issue with the TransactionAutoConfiguration class, particularly regarding its nested package-private @Configuration. I need to understand if registering outer processes affects it. In Spring, I believe nested classes aren’t automatically registered unless they’re explicitly imported. But wait, it seems that the @Configuration class parser processes member classes as configuration candidates, which means they do get registered. So, I think I’ve cleared up that point about how these classes are handled!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_YpNSeJ68e9dXc4fZBNyY7KPI|fc_0b6d12dcd4a085b5016a0bca3e61c88193ac7ddf28851f451d", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "TXJAR=$(find ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.springframework/spring-tx/7.0.3 -name 'spring-tx-*.jar' | head -1); javap -classpath \"$TXJAR\" org.springframework.transaction.support.TransactionOperations", "timeout": 10}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 851, "output": 840, "cacheRead": 34816, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 36507, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1779157550360, "respon